# A history of sustainability at UCSC

Typically when you imagine college clubs you might picture them pertaining to certain hobbies or similar interests. This is true at the University of California Santa Cruz (UCSC) however, many of the most active student groups today have a focus on sustainability and the environment. The origins of that focus can be traced back to a rich history of sustainability at UCSC. This deep history has shaped a sense of culture built on activism and encouraging social change within the community.  

UCSC’s approach to sustainability is something that is fundamental to the mission of the university, as can be seen through the [sustainability plan](https://sustainabilityplan.ucsc.edu/) listed on their website. The university has continued an initiative to promote sustainability on campus through a plan that consists of major goals like, decarbonization and a fossil-free future on campus , building communities of care, and having an advanced circular economy when it comes to consumption. The history of this sustainable consciousness which is fundamental to UCSC and amongst one of its top priorities, is what has sparked future generations to also advocate and come together through the use of clubs and organization with an ultimate goal of protecting our planet.   

One of the most significant gatherings that has been born out of this tradition of an active mindset is the yearly [Earth Summit](https://www.enviroslug.org/earth-summit). Starting in 2002, the formerly established Student Environmental Center (SEC) held what would later be known as their first Earth Summit, with the goal in mind of bringing the community together to discuss the state of sustainability at UCSC. One of the most notable accomplishments of that first Earth Summit was the establishment of the Chancellor’s Sustainability Action Council (CSAC) which led to. A support group designed to “help institutionalize and coordinate the ongoing efforts of the working groups.” Through the initiative of CSAC and these working groups, the projects and issues identified at Earth Summit could be put to action. While CSAC was the first steps in coordinating sustainability efforts on campus and created during the first Earth Summit, campus sustainability efforts are now led by the [UCSC Sustainability Office](https://sustainability.ucsc.edu/) and the Campus Sustainability Council, which is a sub-section that works directly with the council.   
    
![][image1]

Students gathered for the 23rd annual Earth Summit. May 3, 2025\. [https://www.enviroslug.org/earth-summit](https://www.enviroslug.org/earth-summit) 

Over the years, Earth Summit has grown into one of UCSC’s longest-running traditions. Earth Summit has worked to develop themes that match both global and local climate concerns. For example, the Earth Summit in 2025 focused on “Cultivating Climate Action,” through the use of workshops, community murals, student initiatives to present issues, and guest speakers. This sense of sustainability has been maintained by the institution through events and organizations which have shaped the culture here on campus. It has created a natural environment for student-led sustainability clubs to exist, but also flourish.The group [Enviroslug](https://www.enviroslug.org/earth-summit) is a culmination of the history of sustainability at UCSC. Together, it consists of student-led agendas like the Education for Sustainable Living Program (ESLP), Campus Sustainability Council (CSC), and the Student Environmental Center (SEC). By integrating sustainability into everything it does, from building design to waste diversion plans, UCSC has created an environment where students passionate about environmental justice don’t have to fight previous setbacks that are often experienced elsewhere. UCSC’s continued history of sustainability on campus only enhances the platform and legitimacy of these students’ efforts.   

Outside observers have also come to notice UCSC’s sustainability efforts. [The Princeton Review](https://news.ucsc.edu/2011/04/princeton-review-green-campuses/) has consistently ranked UCSC among the top “green colleges” in the nation by citing waste diversion efforts, student activism, sustainable transportation, and administrative dedication to the environment.   

As the efforts continue on campus, the culture around sustainability continues to grow with it. The presence of clubs like enviroslug, the SEC, and the ESLP, help to reflect the foundation the university has built over the history of its existence  

For new students, this means that getting involved in sustainability should be pretty easy. Students who care about environmental justice, climate issues, or simply just  meeting others with similar interests, can easily find a place to start on campus. The long history of sustainability at UCSC has worked to create a campus environment where environmental responsibility feels almost natural and heavily supported.   

In the end, UCSC’s commitment to sustainability influences more than just policy decisions. It gives students real opportunities to participate and continue the initiative that the groups before them began. The clubs that exist today carry that history forward, and they will continue to carry influence on campus life in the future.
